deck_excerpt: The deck is primarily a Pendulum-based Spellcaster deck, featuring monsters like Endymion, the Mighty Master of Magic and Magister of Endymi
deck_description: The deck is primarily a Pendulum-based Spellcaster deck, featuring monsters like Endymion, the Mighty Master of Magic and Magister of Endymion. Its strategy revolves around using a large number of Spell Cards to place Spell Counters on the monsters, which then enables them to use powerful effects. The deck also includes generic support cards such as Pot of Desires and Triple Tactics Talent. The overall theme is based on powerful magic and sorcery.

My interpretation of a modern Yami Yugi/Atem for domain format.

 

Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning is the DM

How To Play

Stall until you get into a favorable position to summon your boss monsters! Arcana Force 0 - The Fool, Fairy Box, and Dark Sanctuary block your opponent's attacks. Arcana Force XIV - Temperance prevents OTKs with its discard effect. Desperado Barrel Dragon and Blowback Dragon break boards with their destruction effects. Lastly, Arcana Force XIX - The Sun is your main boss monster. It can easily special summon itself from your hand and provides great benefits via its summon effect. The outcome is uncertain, but one thing is clear, will you leave it up to fate?

On Arcana Spread

Arcana Spread is a key support card for this deck. It works with every coin flip card except Second Coin Toss, which doesn’t flip coins by itself.

Arcana Spread's first effect lets you flip a coin, then special summon a monster depending on the result. If you flip heads, you can special summon Arcana Force 0 - The Fool from your deck. If you flip tails, you can special summon a coin flip monster from your graveyard. There are no restrictions on Arcana Spread's effect, so you can either special summon The Fool as a wall or tribute fodder or revive a coin flip monster for free. This effect works best when you have a coin flip monster in your graveyard and a copy of The Fool in your deck. The best coin flip monsters to revive are Goddess of the Two Sides, who can search for another coin flip monster if she's special summoned, and your boss monster Arcana Force XIX - The Sun. Blowback Dragon and Desperado Barrel Dragon are also great targets, as both of them have destruction effects.

Arcana Spread's second effect banishes itself from your graveyard to add a different coin flip card from your graveyard to your hand, except Second Coin Toss. This recycles nearly every coin flip card in your deck and enables some insane grind games. You don't need to run multiple copies of your less important cards because of it.

You can only use 1 Arcana Spread effect per turn, but the benefits are worth it!

Tech Cards

Origami Goddess is cracked in the mirror match, as she'll always double her attack whenever a coin flip effect resolves with heads.

Dicephoon is a great addition to every deck for this event, as it has a high chance of destroying either 1 or 2 spells and/or traps.

Some Tips

Arcana Force XIX - The Sun's heads effect can set Arcana Spread, Cup of Ace, or Dark Sanctuary directly from your deck. Arcana Force XIX - The Sun's tails effect is this event's version of Heavy Storm. It clears the field by destroying every card in the spell and trap zones.

Setting multiple backrow on turn 1 is risky, as the opponent's Arcana Force XIX - The Sun can destroy them on their turn. Activating Dark Sanctuary is a safe play, as The Sun can't destroy it. You can safely set Blind Obliteration if you control no face-up coin flip monsters. You can also set Head Judging to bait out or negate The Sun. Do not normal summon any coin flip monster on turn 1, because your opponent might summon The Sun. Setting Arcana Force 0 - The Fool or passing with Arcana Force XIV - Temperance in hand are optimal plays, as this format lacks monster removal and few decks can OTK immediately.

Play conservatively with your Second Coin Toss and don't activate more than 1 at a time. It's an important card that can't be recovered. It helps you rig your coin flips in your favor.

deck_name: More than Great- A Pure Salamangreat Deck
deck_description:
This is the deck that I tweaked to the point where it's taking out Ryzeal and sometimes even Maliss, if you go first and keep up the destruction pressure.

The key is Salamangreat of Fire, of course, but even a moderate hand can recover a card with Sunlight Wolf and then hop into Princess to grab SW back and go into a Ressurection-Linked Ragin Pheonix for a guaranteed negate with Roar. That means you end with AT LEAST one negate, one destruction prevention with Baelynx, one destruction/revive with Princess which you can use Raging for cost to revive the Raging in the graveyard with 5600 Atk, and the revival effect of Raging in case you didn't use it in the previous point. If you're filthy rich in materials, which can happen, you can even use Code of Soul to Ressurection Link Summon a Pyro Pheonix on the enemy's turn for a board wipe! It's super hard to fully grind to a halt because of all the recursion, the amount of handtraps means you will probably have at least two in starting, and it's out of meta, so there's a chance it'll catch people off guard.

ENJOY!

deck_excerpt: THE STRONGEST FLIP ARCHETYPE OF ALL TIME! THE STRONGEST BURN ARCHETYPE OF ALL TIME!
deck_description:
Enneacraft is a really neat archetype released in Phantom Revengers. The main gameplan of the deck is to flip your monsters whenever you want/can, accumulate counters on your pendulum zone monsters, and then burn your opponent for 8100 LP using the field spell.

The side deck is not a conventional side deck, moreso a "suggestion" zone. You could play these cards and they could be really useful, but the deck runs fine as is without them.

The decklist from the popular YugiTuber, Teamsamuraix1's Raidraptor deck, but now it's in UR hands

 

(it's also a really good deck for budget duelists)

The Power of Fellows Structure Deck with the new cards that support Junk Warrior and friends, referencing the final Duel in 5D’s, is just alright. 5D’s is my favorite of the series, and the final Duel between Yusei and Jack that this Structure Deck is probably one of the greatest Duels throughout every Yu-Gi-Oh series, next to some of the greats like Jaden vs Yugi, Atem vs Yugi, Soulburner vs Revolver, Yuma vs Astral, and whatnot. The new cards attempt to centralize around a strategy that focuses on OTKing your opponent with the new Junk Warrior Extreme which essentially Soul Charges a bunch of Level 2 or lower monsters back from your GY on Synchro Summon, and this is because when it destroys a monster by battle, you can banish it to Special Summon Junk Warrior from your Extra Deck which is treated as a Synchro Summon. And if you didn’t know, on Synchro Summon, Junk Warrior gains ATK equal to the total ATK of all Level 2 or lower monsters you currently control. Essentially, you are trying to recreate the scene where Yusei has Junk Synchron, Quillbolt Hedgehog, Sonic Chick, Speed Warrior, and Sonic Warrior on field, Synchros Junk Warrior using Junk Synchron and Sonic Warrior, and then you have Chain Link 1 Junk Warrior’s effect on Synchro Summon to gain ATK and Chain Link 2 Sonic Warrior’s effect in GY which pumps all your Level 2 or lower monsters by 500 ATK (400 ATK in the anime). While this makes for an incredible finisher in the anime, it doesn’t really do much in real life, given that the new cards are just more ways to get to Junk Speeder due to the whole Junk Warrior OTK thing being unbelievably bad. Like just play Tachyon or something. And with the disappointing reveal of the Structure Deck’s final card in Synchro Oneway, I’m just going to post the current list I have for Prediction Princess which utilizes the new cards from the Structure Deck. 

The new Synchron and/or Junk Warrior cards (however you may call them) are great for turboing out Level 5 Synchro Monsters, which doesn’t come as a surprise since both Junk Warrior and Junk Speeder are Level 5. I initially tried making a Deck with a Synchron engine to make the Level 5 monster, Ib the World Chalice Justiciar, while also filling the rest of the Deck with Runick cards to immediately put out a Level 9 monster, but that is a bit boring. So, I decided to just put more Synchron cards into the Deck to Synchro out a Level 9 monster instead. For this, I needed either Level 4 or Level 2 extenders, but the new extenders from the Structure Deck Synchro-lock you for the rest of the turn, so I chose to play cards that are searchable in the Deck, just not ones that are searchable by the new Junk Warrior support cards.

Full combo is either Assault Synchron or Satellite Synchron, Fullspeed Warrior, and a discard. Let’s say that we have Assault Synchron. Normal Summon Fullspeed Warrior and use its effect on Normal Summon to search for Synchro Fellows. Activate Synchro Fellows to search for Junk Synchron and Scrap Synchron, discarding 1 card. Synchro Summon Scrap Warrior using Fullspeed Warrior on field and Scrap Synchron in hand because Scrap Synchron can do that. On Synchro Summon, Scrap Warrior searches for another Junk Synchron (this will be used for your next turn). Activate Synchro Fellows in GY, banishing it from GY and targeting Scrap Warrior. Synchro Fellows decreases Scrap Warrior’s Level by 1 and then you can also Normal Summon a Synchron monster in addition to your Normal Summon/Set this turn. Normal Summon Junk Synchron and activate its effect on Normal Summon to Special Summon Fullspeed Warrior from GY with its effects negated. Activate Assault Synchron in hand, Special Summoning it and taking 700 damage. Synchro Junk Synchron and Fullspeed Warrior into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches for World Legacy Monstrosity on Synchro Summon. Synchro Assault Synchron and Scrap Warrior into Herald of the Arc Light. Synchro Ib and Herald into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. Herald triggers as it is sent to GY which searches for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate Monstrosity targeting Crocodragon to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck. Xyz PIXIEA and Crocodragon into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ. Aggregator sends Wind Pegasus @Ignister from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and then you can use its other effect to target Herald in GY, detach 1 material, and attach Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller, and Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons PIXIEA from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and then Tarotrei can flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect then Special Summons Deus-X Krawler from your Deck face-down and can also use its other effect to flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and PIXIEA face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for another Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell and it protects your Ritual Monsters from targeting and destruction by your opponent’s effects while it is face-up on the field. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it’s flipped face-up. And PIXIEA prevents your opponent from targeting cards on either field or in either GY with card effects after it has been flipped face-up. Oh, and that Junk Synchron that you searched off of Scrap Warrior earlier can be Normal Summoned on your following turn to Synchro with a Level 9 monster to make Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. 2 Junk Synchron which targets a Level 2 or lower monster in your GY on Normal Summon and Special Summons it with its effects negated. Synchro Fellows requires that you also search a Junk Synchron in addition to a card that mentions Junk Warrior or Stardust Dragon, so it’s best if you play at least 2 Junk Synchron in your Deck to ensure that you can actually activate Fellows when you are trying to set-up your combo. 3 Assault Synchron which can Special Summon itself from your hand, and then it inflicts 700 damage to you and you cannot Special Summon from the Extra Deck while it's in the Monster Zone when Special Summoned this way except for Synchro Monsters. Can’t actually use its other effect in this Deck, but that is fine. 2 Satellite Synchron, which we are mainly using for its first effect which allows you to Special Summon it from your hand when a monster(s) is Special Summoned from your GY. You could use its second effect to make its Level become 4 for the turn if you have a Synchro Monster with Warrior, Synchron, or Stardust in its original name on field or in GY, but in this Deck, you can’t really benefit from that. Assault Synchron and Satellite Synchron are basically what we are playing as our Level 2 extenders. Those Level 2 extenders could be Tuners or non-Tuners as it does not matter, but the searchable Anchorbolt Hedgehog locks you into Synchro Monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn, which is not what we want. Even the original Quillbolt Hedgehog would be better than Anchorbolt in this case, except that it is not searchable. 1 Scrap Synchron which can be used as Synchro Material from hand if you Synchro Summon a monster that mentions a Synchron Tuner as material and it can substitute itself for any Synchron Tuner for the Synchro Summon of a monster. Just a great card in general, especially with its associated Synchro Monster, Scrap Warrior. 3 Fullspeed Warrior which adds Junk Synchron or a Spell/Trap that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck to your hand. 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Reinforcement of the Army. 3 Synchro Fellows which adds a Junk Synchron and a monster that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck to your hand and then you discard a card. You can also banish it from GY and target a Synchro Monster you control to decrease that monster’s Level by 1 and then give yourself another Normal Summon of a Synchron monster in addition to your Normal Summon/Set this turn. 3 Tuning which searches a Synchron Tuner from Deck and then sends the top card of your Deck to the GY. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon which can Quick Effect target a face-up monster on the field or in either GY during the Main Phase and place it face-up in its owner’s Spell/Trap Zone. And then during the Battle Phase, you can Quick Effect target 1 monster and 1 Continuous Spell on the field and destroy them. As previously mentioned, Junk Synchron and Level 9 monster can make Vengeance Dragon which is really nice for clean-up on a following turn. Centur-Ion Legatia is another card you can make that has 12 stars and it draws you a card and destroys your opponent’s monster with the highest ATK if it is Special Summoned. However, Vengeance Dragon still is the better option for a 12 star Synchro. And since you also are playing Level 2 Tuners, you can also decide on playing Psychic End Punisher. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. It gains 500 ATK/DEF for each card in your hand and on Synchro Summon, it can draw you cards equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon, which is usually going to be just 1. You aren’t going to really use its last effect which is to Quick Effect discard 2 cards and target and destroy a card on field, but you could play Nine-Lives Cat to bring it back and use Crocodragon as both removal and a Level 9 body on a following turn. 1 Wind Pegasus @Ignister which we are just playing because we can either go into it when Synchro climbing into Crocodragon or just through sending it off of Mereologic Aggregator. If another card(s) you control is destroyed by battle or your opponent’s card effect while it’s on field or in GY, you can banish it to target and shuffle a card your opponent controls back into the Deck. In the combo I laid out earlier, we Synchro climbed into Herald before making Crocodragon and instead sent Wind Pegasus to GY via Aggregator. Because of this, you don’t necessarily have to play Wind Pegasus. You could play Garura, Wings of Resonant Life for a draw or you can play Fossil Warrior Skull Knight or Fossil Machine Skull Wagon for a way to put a monster or Spell/Trap pop into rotation, respectively. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which, if sent to GY, can search for either a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck. 1 Scrap Warrior which searches takes a Junk Synchron or a card that mentions Junk Warrior from your Deck and either adds it to hand or sends it to GY on Synchro Summon. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, 1 S:P Little Knight, and 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 1 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Fire format isn't finished yet... It's flames are still alive and well!
deck_description:
Fire format isn't finished yet... It's flames are still alive and well like a Phoenix (or Garunix) rising from the ashes! It turns out that despite the many banlist hits effectively extinguishing Snake-Eyes, Fire King can be used as a crutch to put the heat back into this fire format strategy! Dust off the good ol' Snake-Eyes Ash, Promethean Princess, Hiita the Fire Charmer and Bonfire, FIRE FORMAT ISN'T EXTINGUISHED YET!

Fire King provides so much extension, recursion, bodies and utility to the Snake-Eyes strategy. Almost EVERYTHING floats you into either more giant beatsticks on field or more resources in-hand. Piloted properly, Snake-Eye Fire King definitely can compete in ladder where Maliss and Ryzeal are dominant! It can also deal with Maxx "C," counter stun decks, and dominate every strategy with it's massive bodies, recursion and resources!

If you want a detailed guide on how to play the deck, click here!

deck_excerpt: I mean, there are Insects in the combo
deck_description:
I was feeling inspired, so I went back to the Krawler Prediction Princess Deck that I previously made, and I wanted to improve on the Deck. The issue with Krawler Prediction Princess lies solely with Krawler Soma which is literally not searchable. It CAN be searched by cards like the Krawler monsters (Krawler Axon, Krawler Dendrite, Krawler Glial, Krawler Ranvier, Krawler Receptor, and Krawler Spine), but the Krawler monsters have to leave your control by your opponent’s card effect and then they Special Summon Krawler monsters from your Deck face-down. We want either to add Soma to hand or Special Summon it face-up. World Legacy’s Mind Meld also has the same issue as it Special Summons a Krawler monster from your hand, Deck, or GY face-down to a zone a Link Monster points to. World Legacy Survivor can technically add Soma to hand if it is in the top 5 cards of your Deck that you excavate, but it’s not that reliable in a non-dedicated Krawler Deck, especially since there are only 3 Soma that can be in a Deck. And then you have Resonance Insect, the main card that puts Insect monsters from your Deck into rotation in most Insect Decks. Unless you are playing an actual Insect archetype or a Deck with a lot of Insect monsters, Resonance Insect is not that helpful. There are a ton of Insect extenders that Special Summon themselves from hand, and because most LINK-2 Insect Link Monsters require only Insects as Link Material, you need to play a good number of Insect monsters and Insect extenders to make the best use of Resonance Insect. But something that did really work for me in the Krawler Prediction Princess Deck was the combination of Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown, Ultimate Great Insect, and Inzektor Picofalena, which essentially translated 3 Insects monsters into 2 Level 9’s on the field to make Mereologic Aggregator. So, I decided to make this new Krawler Prediction Princess Deck into more of like an Insect Prediction Princess Deck focused around those 3 cards to make Aggregator. Now, I did try to play a whole bunch of Insect monsters that could either translate to multiple monsters as well as many Insect extenders, but those failed in 2 aspects. First of all, you needed to open some number of these Insect monsters in a Deck that could more or less not play Resonance Insect to the best of its ability. Second, there were no great ways of putting a 1500 DEF Insect monster on field for Picofalena to equip Beargram from Deck to to make it at least a 2000 DEF Insect monster equipped with an Equip Card to Tribute to Special Summon Ultimate Great Insect. Inzektor could probably make this actually happen, but I’m not willing to learn how to play Inzektor at this point in time. But luckily, our good friends, Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra can facilitate this entire combo and they are also Plants which we can banish for Beargram.

Full combo is Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, a Prediction Princess card, and a monster. If the Prediction Princess card is like a Ritual Monster, it can be used as the monster send for Scorpio’s effect, but you still need another card to discard for the cost of Picofalena’s effect. If the Prediction Princess card is a Ritual Spell or Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, you are going to want to discard a different card for Picofalena’s effect. Let’s say that the Prediction Princess card is Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Normal Summon Scorpio and use its effect on Normal Summon to send Tarotrei from your hand to the GY to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Because it was Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster’s effect, Cobra can add Instant Fusion from Deck to hand. Xyz Cobra and Scorpio into Number 3: Cicada King. Activate Instant Fusion, paying 1000 LP to Special Summon Beetrooper Cruel Saturnas from Extra Deck. Activate Saturnas’s effect on Special Summon to add Beetrooper Descent from Deck. Activate Descent to Special Summon a Beetrooper Token. Link Saturnas and the Token into Inzektor Picofalena. On Link Summon, Picofalena discards a card to target Cicada King and equip Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown from your Deck to it, pumping it by 500 ATK/DEF. Since Cicada King now has 3000 DEF and is equipped with an Equip Card, you can Tribute it to Special Summon Ultimate Great Insect from your Extra Deck. Then, you can banish 3 Insect and/or Plant monsters from your GY (you have Cobra, Scorpio, Cruel Saturnas, and Cicada King to choose from) to Special Summon Beargram from your GY. Xyz Beargram and Ultimate Great Insect into Mereologic Aggregator. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers from being sent to GY to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator and Picofalena into S:P Little Knight. Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Tarotreith in hand to Ritual Summon Tarotrei from GY face-up. During the End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon Tarotreith from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and you can Chain the effect of Tarotrei, targeting Tarotreith to flip it face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from your Deck face-down. And then on a new Chain, you can use Tarotreith’s other effect to flip Deus-X and Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from your Deck while also protecting your Rituals from being targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects while it’s face-up on the field. Deus-X, after it has been flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field. And then, you, of course, have S:P Little Knight for another piece of interaction.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown. It is a Level 9 EARTH Insect monster who cannot be Normal Summoned/Set and must be Special Summoned from your hand or GY by banishing 3 Insect and/or Plant monsters from your hand and/or GY. It prevents your opponent from activating monster effects in response to your Spell/Trap Card or effect activations and once per turn, it can destroy all face-up monsters on the field except Insects and Plants but it cannot attack directly for the rest of the turn. Unless you are Cimo in his Master Duel Masochist series, you aren’t using Beargram for any of its effects other than its effect to Special Summon itself, which isn’t even an effect since it’s a Summoning Condition. Because your Deck isn’t just Plants and Insects, Beargram’s boardwipe effect is more likely to hurt you than your opponent. And it’s not like we are keeping it around to actually make use of its floodgate-esque protection effect either since it’s going straight to being a material for Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Whirlwind Weasel whose Flip Effect prevents your opponent from activating any Spell/Trap Cards for the rest of the turn. You could play a second Deus-X instead of Weasel or even a Guard Dog. In the case that we do draw Deus-X and have no way of putting it onto the field, you want to have another Flip Monster in Deck who can just end your opponent’s turn if possible. As good of a card for protecting your board and floodgating out your opponent Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA is, I don’t know if it has the same stopping power as Whirlwind Weasel or Guard Dog. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. As for Cobra, if it is Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster’s effect, it can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from your Deck to your hand once per Duel. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. Notably, if you go Lonefire into Lonefire into Lonefire into Scorpio, you are putting more Plants into your GY which means that on a following turn, you can banish these Plants from GY to Special Summon Beargram from GY as either an extender or a Level 9 body for a Rank 9 play. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. Another monster you can choose to play in this Deck is Ragnaraika Samurai Beetle as it is a good card for bridging with Small World and it is also an extender from hand by placing a banished Insect, Plant, or Reptile on the bottom of your Deck, and if you decide to play the Ragnaraika Link Monsters, if it is used to make one, it can target a Level 4 or lower Insect, Plant, or Reptile in your GY and Special Summon it in Defense. 

For Spell/Traps:  Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Small World. 1 Beetrooper Descent which Special Summons a Beetrooper Token which is a Level 3 EARTH Insect monster with 1000 ATK/DEF. Can’t actually make use of the rest of its effect to pop a Spell/Trap on field, but this is the card you are getting off of Saturnas to make Picofalena. 1 Called by the Grave. 1 Instant Fusion which is only for getting Beetrooper Cruel Saturnas in this Deck. Now, let’s say that you draw Instant Fusion in your opening hand. What are you searching with Cobra? While we aren’t playing any other targets in Deck, you could play Super Polymerization maybe like 1 or 2 copies of it alongside Garura, Wings of Resonant Life alongside Mudragon of the Swamp in the Extra Deck and maybe a Starving Venom Fusion Dragon if you so please. You could also play Miracle Synchro Fusion to be able to Fusion Summon Coordius the Triphasic Dealmon on a following turn and pay 4000 LP to add a Spell/Trap from your GY to your hand and then destroy 3 cards your opponent controls. If we could put a Level 6 or higher Synchro Monster into the GY in our combo, then you know that we would be using Miracle Synchro Fusion to make Saint Azamina to further floodgate our opponent and also Special Summon Azamina Ilia Silvia from Extra Deck for an omni-negate. You could even be playing Fusion Armament to reveal something like a Gaia Drake, the Universal Force in your Extra Deck to Special Summon a Gaia Knight, the Force of Earth from your Extra Deck as an extender. But besides that, the last Spell/Trap we are playing is 3 copies of Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Ultimate Great Insect which can be Special Summoned from your Extra Deck by Tributing an Insect monster with 2000 or more DEF that’s equipped with an Equip Card. 1 Beetrooper Cruel Saturnas which we are getting off of Instant Fusion as mentioned before and it can add a Beetrooper card from Deck to hand on Special Summon. If we were playing Prediction Ritual and Pre-Preparation of Rites in the Main Deck, then I would recommend also playing Master of Ham in the Extra Deck, but since we aren’t there’s no Ham here. 1 Elder Entity N’tss. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Number 3: Cicada King which is a generic Rank 3 Insect Xyz Monster we can make with Cobra and Scorpio that has a 2500 DEF booty on it which makes it able to be Tributed for Ultimate Great Insect as soon as an Equip Card is equipped to it. But, since Picofalena equips an Insect monster from Deck to an Insect monster you control as an Equip Spell that gives it 500 ATK/DEF, Number 20: Giga-Brilliant also works here (Giga-Brilliant can also pump itself up to 2100 DEF by detaching 1 anyways). 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Inzektor Picofalena which on Link Summon can discard a card and target another Insect monster you control to equip an Insect monster from Deck to it as an Equip Spell that gives it 500 ATK/DEF. Notably, you can also be playing some of the Ragnaraika Link Monsters, but if you do, I would recommend playing Ragnaraika Chain Coils which is a semi-generic LINK-4 that just needs 2+ monsters including an Insect, Plant, or Reptile as material. Basically, if your opponent activates a monster effect, you can make it so that neither player can activate effects of monsters in hand this turn. It works surprisingly nice with Deus-X’s effect since you are now covering both your opponent’s field and hand for monster effects. And you can definitely make this card by including an additional extender somewhere in your combo or by choosing to play Fusion Armament like I mentioned earlier and then have the possibility of making this card if you draw either Instant Fusion or Fusion Armament in your opening hand. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 3 Evenly Matched, 3 Solemn Judgment.

deck_name: Fiendsmith Yummy K9 Vanquish Soul Tenpai
deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith Yummy K9 Vanquish Soul Tenpai
deck_description: Fiendsmith Yummy K9 Vanquish Soul Tenpai

Looking back on my Predaplant Prediction Princess list, there are quite a few things that I can improve on. But, let’s begin on where my previous list failed. First of all, it was a list that I made when I was focusing on experimenting with every Level 9 monster in the game to see which one could help to facilitate the best version of Prediction Princess. The Level 9 monster I focused on in my Predaplant Prediction Princess Deck was Predaplant Triphyoverutum, a Level 9 Fusion Monster, that requires 3 DARK monsters on the field as Fusion Material. Triphyoverutum is not a hard monster to properly Summon, but when you compare it to many other Level 9 monsters, it requires more investment than those other monsters. So, the Level 9 monster I focused on was not the most optimal Level 9 monster to focus on. The second issue with the Deck is that it required the usage of World Legacy Monstrosity to get the necessary Level 9 bodies on field to make Mereologic Aggregator and prepare to transition to Prediction Princess plays. Monstrosity is not searchable in that Deck, so it is not the most reliable Deck for getting to full Prediction Princess combo. And third, because this Deck was the first time I even considered using a Predaplant engine to facilitate a Prediction Princess Deck, it was not my best attempt at doing so. There are so many Prediction Princess Decks that I have made after that which utilize the Predaplant engine way better, excluding the ones that also use Red Resonator of course (but those were still great at getting to the worse of the Level 9’s I’ve had to work with). But, I am speaking of Decks like Fiendsmith Prediction Princess (this list could still be updated to be better), Gold Pride Prediction Princess (I have an updated list I haven’t put out yet), and Insect Prediction Princess. So, this new version of Predaplant Prediction Princess should get rid of the whole “having to use Triphyoverutum” part of it, not focus on using Monstrosity when it is not searchable, and it should make the best use out of not only the Predaplant engine, but the playable Predaplant cards as well.

The cards you need to open for this Deck’s combo are the exact same as for Insect Prediction Princess. You just need Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, a Prediction Princess card, and a monster to send to GY as cost for Scorpio’s effect. Let’s say that the Prediction Princess card is Prediction Princess Tarotrei which means you can just send it to GY for Scorpio’s effect and not need another monster to send as cost. Normal Summon Scorpio and activate its effect, sending Tarotrei from your hand to GY, and Special Summoning Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio from Deck. Since Cobra was Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster’s effect, it can search for Instant Fusion from Deck. Pay 1000 LP to activate Instant Fusion to Special Summon Predaplant Ambulomelides. On Fusion Summon, Ambulomelides adds Predapruning from Deck to hand. Activate Ambulomelides’s other effect targeting itself to Tribute itself and Special Summon Predaplant Banksiogre from Deck. Synchro Banksiogre and Scorpio into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. On Synchro Summon, Crocodragon activates to draw you a card and Banksiogre activates in GY as a mandatory activation to place Predator Counters on all monsters your opponent controls when it leaves the field. Activate Predapruning to Special Summon back Banksiogre from GY and equip it with it. Synchro Banksiogre and Cobra into Cloudcastle. Banksiogre triggers in GY again as its mandatory effect is not a once per turn. Xyz Corocodragon and Cloudcastle into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers from being sent to GY to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller. Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Tarotreith in hand to Ritual Summon Tarotrei from GY face-up. During the End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon Tarotreith from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and you can Chain the effect of Tarotrei, targeting Tarotreith to flip it face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from your Deck face-down. And then on a new Chain, you can use Tarotreith’s other effect to flip Deus-X and Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from your Deck while also protecting your Rituals from being targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects while it’s face-up on the field. Deus-X, after it has been flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field. It’s the standard Prediction Princess set-up which is completely carried by Deus-X’s effect, but you still have your handtraps available in hand which is nice. However, you can always cut down on the non-engine to play stuff like Prediction Ritual and Pre-Preparation of Rites for more consistency.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Guard Dog whose Flip Effect prevents your opponent from Special Summoning for the rest of the turn. Again, you could play a second copy of Deus-X or Whirlwind Weasel instead of this card, but make sure it has a lot of stopping power. 1 Predaplant Banksiogre which is a Level 6 Predaplant Tuner monster because Yuri used it and a Token to Synchro Summon Clear Wing in the anime. Because y’know, you can just spawn a Predaplant Tuner monster out of nowhere between the Duels that happened inside Duel Academia, the entirety of which lasted in the span of a couple hours max. Just remember that its effect in GY after it leaves the field is a mandatory activation even if your opponent has no monsters for you to place Predator Counters on. Notably, this card is also a hard brick in the Deck, so just cry if you draw it. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. If Cobra is Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster’s effect, it can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from your Deck to your hand once per Duel. Notably, Cobra is also a hard brick in the Deck, so you have 2 hard bricks that you need to worry about. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird.

For Spell/Traps:  Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Predapruning which is not a brick, but you would still rather not draw it either way. It’s an Equip Spell that targets a Predaplant in GY, Special Summons it, and then equips it with this card. When Predapruning leaves the field, that monster is destroyed. 3 Small World. 1 Instant Fusion for Ambulomelides, but if you do decide to play Pre-Prep and Prediction Ritual, you should also play Master of Ham in the Extra Deck to potentially go with these cards. 1 Earthbound Fusion. It’s a Quick-Play Spell, but there’s no card in a Field Zone, it can only be activated during the Main Phase. It essentially just Fusion Summons a DARK Fusion Monster by using monsters from your hand or field as material. This is the alternative search off of Cobra if you open Instant Fusion, and you are using this card to Fusion Summon Guardian Chimera on your opponent’s turn. This is probably the best and only card searchable off of Cobra that can do this. It’s not like you can search Branded in Red or something; you aren’t even playing any Despia cards. I guess Chimera Fusion also does the same thing, but you need to also use a Beast, Fiend, or Illusion as material, none of which we have. Now, you could argue that we can be playing Super Polymerization instead, but I disagree as Super Poly is much better as a board breaker than it is as interruption. I mean, do you think that your opponent is really putting that many monsters on their field through Deus-X. If you want to play Super Poly, I’d say that you should keep it in the Side Deck rather than have it start in the Main Deck. Finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Guardian Chimera which requires 3 monsters with different names as material and those monsters need to be either from your hand or your field, with at least 1 from each. On Fusion Summon, if it was Fusion Summoned by a Spell Card or effect, you can draw cards equal to the number of materials used from hand and then destroy cards equal to the number of materials used from field. It is also a Level 9 monster, so it can be used for Rank 9 plays if it sticks around. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides. On Fusion Summon, it adds a Predap card from Deck to hand and you can target 1 monster your opponent controls with a Predator Counter or 1 monster you control to Tribute it and Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. 1 Cloud Castle which targets a Level 9 monster in your GY when it is Synchro Summoned and Special Summons it. Crocodragon replenishes your hand by 1, so what is my reason for choosing to play specifically Cloudcastle you may ask. Let’s say that you draw Bibliomuse as your Prediction Princess card and no other Prediction Princess cards. Heck, let’s also say that the rest of your hand has no monsters besides Scorpio. Well, you can send Bibliomuse from hand to GY for Scorpio’s effect and then Cloudcastle can bring it back when it is Synchro Summoned and you still have full Prediction Princess combo. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Knightmare Unicorn. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Solemn Judgment.

deck_name: Dracotail Combo Lines You’ve Never Seen Before
deck_excerpt: Light End. Dark End. Dracotail Wins
deck_description: I’ve updated my Dracotail deck by adding Light End Dragon and Dark End Dragon to push the ceiling even higher! These changes let me produce boards packed with multiple negates, even trough Nibiru!

deck_excerpt: pulling both witch and MOF because i'm simply that good
deck_description:
Witch's domain is Dark and Spellcaster, access to almost all good effect monsters from MRD, including Sangan and MOF, masked sorc and white hat. SDY picked as starter deck for better dark monsters and better spell trap lineup (worth missing out on jinn)

Soul exchange about to go crazy with half the pulls fr

small zombie subtheme for funsies, and few politics cards in the form of butcher (searchable by witch btw), stern mystic (bro is also last will and sangan target with highest attack) and to some extent paralyzing potion and germ infection

share the pain with witch domain master is actually crazy, shame it isn't worded as "both players tribute one monster" though

Lifegain and Burn over more bodies because witch is always more bodies and lifegain means more witch summons from domain zone, while burn means less domain summons for my opponents. Tremendous Fire is probably the worst card in here (maybe worse than red med even)

deep-seated sounds kinda swag in theory, can keep it recurring while i have bodies or equip it to witch to search a body and then have it recur for that new guy

insane pulls so far, probably telling that even my most sus cards are halfway decent-ish

deck_excerpt: Teaming up with Jaden (Judai) is fun but exhausting...
deck_description: It’s hard to make Elemental Heroes work since they depend on having the right Fusion cards. This deck can either lead to easy wins or devastating losses, depending on drawing luck. The most satisfying way to win is letting a bunch of Elemental Heroes get destroyed, then using Miracle Fusion to summon Shining Flare Wingman and boosting him to around 7000 ATK. Overall, I still win most games with this deck, but teaming up with Jaden’s (Judai’s) braindead AI is exhausting most of the time.

This deck focuses on Synchro Summoning Red Dragon Archfiend boss monsters like Red Supernova Dragon and Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, using Resonators as tuners and the Bystial engine to disrupt the opponent’s graveyard while providing additional bodies for plays. The deck is designed to deliver multiple negates, strong removal, and OTK potential, making it effective both going first (with Synchro bosses + negates) and going second (with board-breaking options).

Just a fun deck that goes for a mix of Control and Swarming-OTK. Trying to break Regenesis.

Let's jam!!

A budget friendly version of punk bystial, under 80.  Upgrades would be triple tactics thrust, harpie's feather storm, and cyber slash harpie lady to add a more potent going first package, or options like the mulcharmies.  Dagda is also an option if you go up against a lot of maliss.

The main idea of this deck is effectively deep draw control.  You spend life points and use the field spell to replenish hand, and can end on juraishin and jam fever to have interaction while being able to replenish LP

Yami Kane Hostile Takeover tournament deck

E-tele / Geek boy / Fire are full combo.  (If you have Fire search Geek then basically follow the same combo)
Geek search Origin, Origin search First Appearance, First Appearance search Fire, Fire search Doombroker, link Ashlan, Ashlan reveal Doombroker search Benten, First Appearance summon Doombroker tribute Benten, Benten search Diviner, Doombroker set intervention, normal Diviner send herald, search Raven, Raven tribute Diviner, Diviner special Poissonniere, Poissonniere search Recette de Poisson/Buerillabaisse.  At some point tribute Raven for a ritual, Raven search Illusion, Illusion search Souls, Souls send Illusion, Souls send Libromancer to draw 2.  From there you can use Ashlan + Souls to go Closed Moon into whatever fiendsmith line you want.  

Libromancer and Fiendsmith really help with going second as well since they dont require normals and have a bunch of incidental removal.  Main line is the same until Benten search:

First Appearance ritual Doombroker, Chain 1 Benten Chain 2 Ashlan bounce effect Chain 3 Origin destroy Spell/Trap.  If Doombroker deals damage he can spin a card (Ashlan gives it piercing to help with this).  Doombroker + Ashan into Dyna Mondo to spin comes up sometimes as well.  Fiendsmith lines heavily depend on the board state/whats in hand but the Desirae + Agnumday lines tend to clean things up.  

Cute synergies:

Fiendsmith links target when equipping from grave to trigger Poeltis.  Desirae also targets and can be used to trigger Buerillabaisse in a pinch.  

Tract can search Chef, Chef can make Requiem, and Aerial Eater can send Chef to revive off Cross-Sheep.

Diviner becomes a 6 after sending Herald and can be used to make Wave High King in a pinch.  

Dyna Mondo can be made using Doombroker to trigger a Nouvelles/to remove something, then on opponents turn you can tag Dyna out to special back Doombroker to turn Intervention back online.  

Veiler/Imperm target to trigger Poeltis.

A fun, casual, Egyptian-themed deck using the Odion/Horus/Ra archetypes. Surprisingly flexible and resilient (for casual play at least), although it can be a little bricky if you don't draw a starter. Only three non-engine cards in the Main Deck (which are all part of the Odion combo line), although only five of the fifteen Extra Deck monsters are in-engine or used for the combos. The rest of the Extra Deck (the Knightmares, IP and S:P, Moon and Goddess, etc.) can be swapped out for whatever you want.

deck_excerpt: Dominate with Dragoon with the best shell for the strategy - Primite Fiendsmith!
deck_description:
Ever wanted to aura farm with Dragoon but haven't found a home for the Deviantart Yugioh OC to pilot it? Are you a Yugi-boomer who wants to play Red-Eyes and Dark Magician competitively and win vs. try-hard meta decks like Ryzeal and Maliss? Well duelist, I have the answer for you - Primite Fiendsmith!

Control your way to victory in a Maliss and Ryzeal dominated format with Primite Fiendsmith! Two grindy control strategies coupled with one of the most broken boss monsters ever printed - Dragoon, is surprisingly powerful! In a simplified gamestate, most meta decks would be hardpressed to out such a powerful juggernaut. Fiendsmith Desirae, Primite Drillbeam and Dragoon's recyclable omni-negates are a force to reckon with! Despite this deck's high power ceiling, Primite Fiendsmith can also play "low-to-the-ground," not playing into common "draw" handtraps like Maxx "C," Fuwalos and Purulia! High impact handtraps like Lancea, Droll and Nibiru common in today's metagame hardly affect this deck as well. 

Force your opponent into a grindy control game with your 18 handtraps/staples and come out on top with the triple alliance of Primite, Fiendsmith and Dragoon!

A true modern Ritual deck

Okay so BOOM I am BACK at it again with another MD deck. 

 

SO if you know the Noble/Infernoble combo, you KNOW the end board BUT with the newly added Regenesis cards added to MD recently(as of 9/10/2025) these cards add additional interruptions to our plays. Regenesis Warrior is a super solid fire warrior that can be special summoned via another card with 2500 attack or defense OR by Joyeuse's second effect and the kicker? *Whispers* It recycles itself AND is a quick effect monster. Bro... listen, if you love fire support like me man... you know that ANYTHING that says fire and warrior is something you're gonna look into. But yeah super fun deck if you love combo decks. 

 

And yes I know Blazing Queen Domain is not in MD yet BUT when it does come.. IF it does, it definitely has some use.

deck_excerpt: Ride the wind, bend the meta, and leave nothing but turbulence behind
deck_description:
Turbo Nexus: Winds of Tomorrow is a cutting-edge fusion of Speedroid’s lightning-fast Synchro swarms with the modern dominance of P.U.N.K., Kashtira, and Adventure mechanics. This deck thrives on explosive openings, chaining summon after summon to overwhelm opponents before they can stabilize.

The Speedroid core fuels rapid Synchro climbing into boss monsters like Baronne de Fleur and Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon, while the P.U.N.K. engine adds consistency, graveyard setup, and extra pressure. Kashtira’s zone-locking power turns mid-game into a stranglehold, and the Adventure package shields your plays from disruption, ensuring your combo train never derails.

With multiple win conditions — from OTK bursts to control lockdowns — Turbo Nexus adapts to any matchup, forcing opponents to play your game at your speed. In the current meta, it’s not just about going fast… it’s about staying ahead of the curve.

deck_excerpt: Unchained Deck with Fiendsmith and other fiend support
deck_description: Unchained Deck with Fiendsmith engine that both can bridge into each other whether interrupted or not, along with small mutiny in the sky engine for extra extension if needed. Not a meta deck. Bad match up into the mulcharmies, specifically fuwa and purulia. Fun deck with pretty consistant combos though and okay match up into lower power constructed boards. A strong end board with both unchained and fiendsmith cards would most likely look like: Desirae, Caesar, Unchained soul of rage (into S:P on opponents turn), A Bao, and yama in grave for some recursion if board is destroyed.
